04742nam a22005655i 9780231557641DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2023005692  a97802315576417 a10.7312/newm208822doi  a(DE-B1597)670311  a(OCoLC)1391438810  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHD6508b.N47 2023 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a331.8809732231 aNewman, Lainey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRust Belt Union Blues :bWhy Working-Class Voters Are Turning Away from the Democratic Party /cLainey Newman, Theda Skocpol. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b20 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Figures and Tables -- t1 Understanding Social and Political Change in the Rust Belt -- t2 The Social Underpinnings of the “Union Man” -- t3 The Economic Breakdown of Big Labor from Without and Within -- t4 Union Membership Transformed -- t5 From Union Blue to Trump Red -- t6 On Union Decline and the Potential for Resurgence -- tAppendix A. Voting Patterns in Western Pennsylvania -- tAppendix B. Sample Interview Questions -- tAppendix C. Photographs in IBEW and USW Newsletters -- tAppendix D. Local Union Mentions in IBEW and USW Newsletters -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the heyday of American labor, the influence of local unions extended far beyond the workplace. Unions were embedded in tight-knit communities, touching nearly every aspect of the lives of members—mostly men—and their families and neighbors. They conveyed fundamental worldviews, making blue-collar unionists into loyal Democrats who saw the party as on the side of the working man. Today, unions play a much less significant role in American life. In industrial and formerly industrial Rust Belt towns, Republican-leaning groups and outlooks have burgeoned among the kinds of voters who once would have been part of union communities.Lainey Newman and Theda Skocpol provide timely insight into the relationship between the decline of unions and the shift of working-class voters away from Democrats. Drawing on interviews, union newsletters, and ethnographic analysis, they pinpoint the significance of eroding local community ties and identities. Using western Pennsylvania as a case study, Newman and Skocpol argue that union members’ loyalty to Democratic candidates was as much a product of the group identity that unions fostered as it was a response to the Democratic Party’s economic policies. As the social world around organized labor dissipated, conservative institutions like gun clubs, megachurches, and other Republican-leaning groups took its place.Rust Belt Union Blues sheds new light on why so many union members have dramatically changed their party politics. It makes a compelling case that Democrats are unlikely to rebuild credibility in places like western Pennsylvania unless they find new ways to weave themselves into the daily lives of workers and their families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlue collar workerszUnited States. 0aLabor union membersxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aLabor unionszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aSkocpol, Theda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/newm2088240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557641423Coveruhttps